                    <item>
              <title>ICDE Keynote session: Rory McGreal </title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/5801</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/5801</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Rory spoke about the tipping point that might be coming for OER to topple the Medieval model for universities. He said that there were some myths:</p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Traditional is better than e-learning [no evidence - and people have been looking for it]</li>
<li>E-learning involves less worthwhile contact [no evidence of this and useful contact can be more]</li>
<li>Elearning is 2nd rate [n significant difference]</li>
<li>Small class size is better than large classes [&lt;20 true &gt;30 more students the better.]</li>
<li>Quality of learning is less in elearning. [Elearning introduced quality measures.]</li>
</ul>
<div>Need to ask those who defend traditional models to prove it is better - oherwise internet is essenial for internet. OER quality measures *are* in place. OER avoids the problems of Digital Rights Management that comes with proprietary content that tends to restrict educators from using content as they need to.</div>
<div>He pointed out that the world is going mobile. 1/3 of world population only use mobile when accessing the internet. His advice - Design for Mobile first.&nbsp;</div>
<div>THe OER University now has reached its initial target of 10 member organisations. With a plan to offer a shared open curriculum. OER is part of a changed that is "underhyped" - "If you don't like change you will like irrelevance even less" US General.&nbsp;</div>
<div></div>
</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 04 Oct 2011 06:36:02 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
