                    <item>
              <title>OER11: Cases of OER use: aspects that contribute to successful adoption.</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/5460</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/5460</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Renee Fisher and Jim Greeno</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Looking at reuse of OLI material in Higher Educationking an Activity Theory view of the use of OER as practice.</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Preliminary conclusions:</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->1. Assume OER will be used differently by different instructors. (Also confident that can also be said of learners). Some dependence on subject domain of the OER. &nbsp;&nbsp;</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->2. So do not design for single use. Anticipate various uses &ndash; a &ldquo;pedagogical pachage&rdquo; rather than a course.</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->3. Detail may add or detract E.g.: conceptual explanations facilitate some and detract for others</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Interviewees &ndash; 3 elementary statistics instructors, 2 web design. Interviews every 1-2 weeks. Total of 40 interviews (30-45 minutes). Stats courses use OLI. Web design focussed on web based tools. &nbsp;Different way in which topic functions.</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Three issues for productivity and usability:</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->1. Alignment of OER conceptual focus with previous emphasis</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->2. Match OER topics and sequence with previous syllabus</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->3. Affordances and constraints on instructor-student interaction (e.g. OER providing feedback but only works for some sorts of use)</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->In this talk looking at conceptual focus examples:</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->1. Instructor functioning as a mentor: preparing students to join the community of practice (cf Lave and Wenger). Aim that students join the community of professional web designers). Encourage innovation/exploration. Develop connections through e.g. professional visits, attend conference.</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->2. Instructor functioning as a coach: sees students as cognitive apprentices (Collins). &nbsp;Web resources are tools to help reach goals.</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->3. Knowledge as problem solving and concepts. Use &ldquo;wordy&rdquo; text to explain which software illustrates. OLE leaves it to the technology. [Not previous practice as had emphasised the calculation.</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->a. Preferred by one and will adopt less computation in the future</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->b. Works ok for some students &ndash; produces a different distribution of results.</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->c. Augmented the material to meet curriculum</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Q&amp;A</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Does this mean that we should not seek perfection in OER?</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->An interesting area to go to with this research to investigate what it means for uptake and adoption. How fully developed and specified should things be for release.</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->How is this different in an OER context?</div>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->Interactive approaches can be more intrusive &ndash; tracking by the instructor can cause coercion.</div>
<p>
<p>Renee Fisher and Jim Greeno from Carnegie Mellon University (and OLnet).&nbsp;Looking at reuse of OLI material in Higher Education taking an Activity Theory view of the use of OER as practice.</p>
<p>Preliminary conclusions:</p>
<p><ol>
<li>Assume OER will be used differently by different instructors. (Also confident that this can also be said of learners). Some dependence on subject domain of the OER. &nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
<li>Need to not design for single use. Anticipate various uses &ndash; a &ldquo;pedagogical pachage&rdquo; rather than a course.</li>
<li>Detail may add or detract E.g.: conceptual explanations facilitate some and detract for others</li>
</ol></p>
<p>Interviewees &ndash; 3 elementary statistics instructors, 2 web design. Interviews every 1-2 weeks. Total of 40 interviews (30-45 minutes). Stats courses use OLI. Web design focussed on web based tools. &nbsp;Different way in which topic functions.</p>
<p>Three issues for productivity and usability:</p>
<p><ol>
<li>Alignment of OER conceptual focus with previous emphasis</li>
<li>Match OER topics and sequence with previous syllabus</li>
<li>Affordances and constraints on instructor-student interaction (e.g. OER providing feedback but only works for some sorts of use)</li>
</ol></p>
<p>In this talk looking at conceptual focus examples:</p>
<p>1. Instructor functioning as a mentor: preparing students to join the community of practice (cf Lave and Wenger). Aim that students join the community of professional web designers). Encourage innovation/exploration. Develop connections through e.g. professional visits, attend conference.</p>
<p>2. Instructor functioning as a coach: sees students as cognitive apprentices (Collins). &nbsp;Web resources are tools to help reach goals.</p>
<p>3. Knowledge as problem solving and concepts. Use &ldquo;wordy&rdquo; text to explain which software illustrates. OLE leaves it to the technology. [Not previous practice as had emphasised the calculation.</p>
<p>a. Preferred by one and will adopt less computation in the future</p>
<p>b. Works ok for some students &ndash; produces a different distribution of results.</p>
<p>c. Augmented the material to meet curriculum</p>
<p>Q&amp;A</p>
<p>Does this mean that we should not seek perfection in OER?</p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>An interesting area to go to with this research to investigate what it means for uptake and adoption. How fully developed and specified should things be for release.</li>
</ul>
</p>
<p>How is this different in an OER context?</p>
<p>
<ul>
<li>Interactive approaches can be more intrusive &ndash; tracking by the instructor can cause coercion</li>
</ul>
</p>
</p>
</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Thu, 12 May 2011 11:00:46 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Presentation: OpenSE</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/5450</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/5450</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 24 May 2011 11:41:26 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>OCWC Global 2011: OER Musings and Mapping the OER Landscape</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/5440</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/5440</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>&nbsp;</p>
<div id="_mcePaste" style="cursor:auto"><!--NO CSS-->A combined session with Cathy Casserly and Mike Smith offering their view of the current state of OER and Patrick McAndrew an overview of the work on building an evidence hub that helps share evidence and provide a map of activity in OER.</div>
